{"id": "e08dc4ec11de4a15bf5fce5ec0c1e68e", "timestamp": "2025-12-10 21:23:18", "name": "Scientist1", "content": "Selected Action: **Action 1**.  \nReasoning: While further discussion could refine nuances, our team has already established a robust conceptual foundation that addresses both technical innovation and sociolinguistic depth in Vietnamese hate speech detection. Scientist 1’s proposal of a *context-grounded, sociolinguistically informed generative framework* provides a clear research trajectory that goes beyond surface-level data augmentation by explicitly targeting pragmatic ambiguity, implicit hostility, and culturally indexed language use—key challenges in low-resource NLP. The integration of role-based agents grounded in community-specific discourse norms, adversarial paraphrasing with contextual thread reconstruction, and perceptual validation via native speaker feedback forms a coherent and novel pipeline. This approach not only answers the core question of how to automatically generate a domain-specific dataset but does so in a way that directly tackles the contextual complexity of Vietnamese social media.\n\nMoreover, the proposed evaluation paradigm—focusing on *contextual disambiguation* rather than static classification—ensures that the research output will be measurable and impactful. Given this clarity of vision, selecting the topic now enables us to move swiftly into implementation, pilot testing, and iteration, which is critical for securing funding, building collaborations, and establishing benchmarks. We can continue to refine methodological details in parallel through sub-teams or iterative reviews, but the central research direction is sufficiently mature to commit to at this stage. Early confirmation allows us to advance subsequent work without sacrificing depth.", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[90mScientist1\u001b[0m"}
